value.name: Glen Cove, New York - Wikipedia
value.snippet: Glen Cove was used as a port by English migrants from New England and named Moscheto before 1668. On May 24, 1668, Joseph Carpenter of Warwick 2) of land to the northwest of the Town of Oyster Bay from the Matinecock. Later in that year, he admitted four residents of Oyster Bay as co-partners in the project: brothers Nathaniel, Daniel, and Robert Coles; and Nicholas Simkins.

value.name: Home - City of Glen Cove
value.snippet: Glen Cove offers an eclectic range of activities, programs and events along with restaurants, cafés and breweries to entertain, challenge and nourish your body, mind and soul. The City offers Pickle ball, Bocce, basketball and tennis courts along with our baseball, soccer, basketball and junior football leagues for children.

value.name: Glen Cove – Wikipedia
value.snippet: Glen Cove liegt auf 40°52'2" nördlicher Breite und 73°37'40" westlicher Länge und erstreckt sich über 49,73 km², die sich auf 17,32 km² Land- und 32,41 km² Wasserfläche verteilen. Glen Cove liegt an der Nordküste von Long Island. Der hier rund 10 km breite Long Island Sound bildet die Grenze zum gegenüber liegenden Bundesstaat Connecticut.

value.name: Garvies Point Brewery and Restaurant
value.snippet: Located at Garvies Point Marina, our casual and comfortable waterfront restaurant offers indoor and outdoor dining. Enjoy our extensive menu of delicious, handcrafted American cuisine. SEE OUR MENU Waterfront Outdoor Dining Garvies Point Brewery offers amazing food outdoors with an incredible view that makes the experience even more special.

value.name: Home - Glen Cove Hotel - Onset, MA
value.snippet: THE GLEN COVE HOTEL & RESTAURANT Explore a Victorian era beauty while appreciating all of today’s modern luxuries. Just a hour or less from Boston or Providence, you arrive at the Ocean Front Glen Cove Hotel. We offer stunning panoramic views of Onset Bay and the Cape Cod Canal offering private and public balconies.

value.name: Glen Coe - Wikipedia
value.snippet: Glen Coe (Scottish Gaelic: Gleann Comhann pronounced [klan̪ˠˈkʰo.ən̪ˠ]) is a glen of volcanic origins, in the Highlands of Scotland. It lies in the north of the county of Argyll , close to the border with the historic province of Lochaber , within the modern council area of Highland .
